Dialogue: 0,0:14:46.01,0:14:52.03,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}也许我们可以再做一次
Dialogue: 1,0:14:52.03,0:14:56.57,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}if we put a zero here then that will rule out this
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.03,0:14:56.57,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果我们在这里放个0，那么就可以排除这个
Dialogue: 1,0:14:56.57,0:15:00.80,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and then the only way that cell can be illuminated is by putting a light bulb here
Dialogue: 0,0:14:56.57,0:15:00.80,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然后唯一可以照亮这个格子的方法就是在这里放一个灯泡
Dialogue: 1,0:15:00.80,0:15:05.72,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh whoops uh boom okay um
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.80,0:15:05.72,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}噢，又点错了
Dialogue: 1,0:15:05.72,0:15:10.08,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}how's that working pretty good I didn't need this for anything
Dialogue: 0,0:15:05.72,0:15:10.08,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}效果如何？很好。我不需要这个东西了
Dialogue: 1,0:15:10.08,0:15:14.88,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}maybe I want this light bulb to infer something in the middle
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.08,0:15:14.88,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}也许我想让这个灯泡推断出中间的一些东西来
Dialogue: 1,0:15:14.88,0:15:19.36,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}trying to think of a good way to do that um
Dialogue: 0,0:15:14.88,0:15:19.36,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我在想一个好办法来做到这个事情
Dialogue: 1,0:15:19.36,0:15:27.04,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}did we need that? maybe we could just have a two here
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.36,0:15:27.04,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我们需要这个吗？也许我们可以在这里放一个2
Dialogue: 1,0:15:27.04,0:15:31.20,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and then we will have to put two light bulbs there
Dialogue: 0,0:15:27.04,0:15:31.20,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然后我们要在这里放两个灯泡
Dialogue: 1,0:15:31.20,0:15:37.45,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and then maybe this is where the final light bulb goes to eliminate that one
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.20,0:15:37.45,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然后也许这就是最后那一个灯泡的位置，来照亮那个格子
Dialogue: 1,0:15:37.45,0:15:39.17,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and we can check our answer
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.45,0:15:39.17,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}接着我们可以检查一下我们的答案
Dialogue: 1,0:15:39.17,0:15:51.08,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}now uh you know we we erased and and re-added a bunch of things so we really should check our whole solution in order to confirm that the the logic flow is intact
Dialogue: 0,0:15:39.17,0:15:51.08,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}现在我们应该检查一下整个解，以确认逻辑流程是完整的
Dialogue: 1,0:15:51.08,0:15:54.34,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and the way to do that is erase our answer and do a complete test solve
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.08,0:15:54.34,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}做的方法是，我们擦掉我们的答案然后做一个完整的测试过程
Dialogue: 1,0:15:54.34,0:15:56.52,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, let's just pretend we're solving the puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.34,0:15:56.52,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}那么，假装我们在解这个谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:15:56.52,0:16:01.19,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you know I would do all this
Dialogue: 0,0:15:56.52,0:16:01.19,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你知道，我会做这样一些
Dialogue: 1,0:16:01.19,0:16:05.16,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}is there anything I can deduce right now there actually is I can put a light bulb here
Dialogue: 0,0:16:01.19,0:16:05.16,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}有什么我现在就能推断出的吗？事实上，我可以在这里放个灯泡
Dialogue: 1,0:16:05.16,0:16:08.81,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because I know that this cell has to be illuminated and nothing else can light it up
Dialogue: 0,0:16:05.16,0:16:08.81,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为我知道这个格子必须被照亮，而其他地方都不行
Dialogue: 1,0:16:08.81,0:16:13.54,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you know does that spoil the aesthetic of my puzzle going all the way around
Dialogue: 0,0:16:08.81,0:16:13.54,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这会破坏我之前设计的绕整个网格一圈的逻辑流的美感吗？
Dialogue: 1,0:16:13.54,0:16:17.89,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}well maybe i might decide to fix this or I might decide I just don't care that's fine
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.54,0:16:17.89,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}好吧，我可能会决定去修复这个问题，或者我也可能决定不管它，问题不大
Dialogue: 1,0:16:17.89,0:16:20.52,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but the intended first step was here
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.89,0:16:20.52,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但我们设计的第一步是在这里
Dialogue: 1,0:16:20.52,0:16:23.78,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and then we can get this light bulb uh
Dialogue: 0,0:16:20.52,0:16:23.78,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然后我们可以得到这个灯泡
Dialogue: 1,0:16:23.78,0:16:26.92,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}sometimes it's interesting to think like what if the player doesn't see this move
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.78,0:16:26.92,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}有时候想一下如果玩家没有看到应该这样走该怎么办？这还挺有意思的
Dialogue: 1,0:16:26.98,0:16:30.69,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like what if the solver just has to go somewhere else can they make progress elsewhere
Dialogue: 0,0:16:26.98,0:16:30.69,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}比如说，如果解题者得从别的位置继续，那他们能在别的位置取得进展吗？
Dialogue: 1,0:16:30.69,0:16:35.56,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um like you might notice that you can't put two here because that would violate the one
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.69,0:16:35.56,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你可能会注意到，你不能在里放两个灯泡，因为那会违反这个1
Dialogue: 1,0:16:35.56,0:16:37.86,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and we need sort of two of these three to be lit up
Dialogue: 0,0:16:35.56,0:16:37.86,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我们需要在三个中的两个位置放灯泡
Dialogue: 1,0:16:37.86,0:16:42.09,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and therefore, this one if it wasn't lit up would force this which would be a contradiction
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.86,0:16:42.09,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因此，如果这个位置没有灯泡，那么就会迫使这里形成矛盾
Dialogue: 1,0:16:42.09,0:16:43.56,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and so, this one has to be lit up
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.09,0:16:43.56,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，这里必须放灯泡
Dialogue: 1,0:16:43.56,0:16:48.23,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}does that help me move forward I’m not sure I think I still need to know which one of these two it is
Dialogue: 0,0:16:43.56,0:16:48.23,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这能帮助我们取得进展吗？还不确定，我想我还是需要知道这两个里面选哪一个
Dialogue: 1,0:16:48.23,0:16:51.49,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and so that would allow me to make that discovery
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.23,0:16:51.49,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}那就会让我取得这样一个发现
Dialogue: 1,0:16:51.49,0:16:53.09,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and then so we get that we get that
Dialogue: 0,0:16:51.49,0:16:53.09,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然后我们得到了这个，又得到了这个
Dialogue: 1,0:16:53.09,0:16:55.85,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}we said that would give us this
Dialogue: 0,0:16:53.09,0:16:55.85,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这会让我们得到这个
Dialogue: 1,0:16:55.85,0:16:57.89,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}which would give us this
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.85,0:16:57.89,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}又让我们得到这个
Dialogue: 1,0:16:57.89,0:17:00.26,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um and then this 2 gives us that
Dialogue: 0,0:16:57.89,0:17:00.26,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然后这个2又让我们确定了这个
Dialogue: 1,0:17:00.26,0:17:02.76,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}that one gives us those two
Dialogue: 0,0:17:00.26,0:17:02.76,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}那个1又确定了这两个
Dialogue: 1,0:17:02.76,0:17:04.17,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}which gives us that
Dialogue: 0,0:17:02.76,0:17:04.17,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这又让我们确定了那个
Dialogue: 1,0:17:04.17,0:17:07.17,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}which then gives us this to sort of force that
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.17,0:17:07.17,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然后确定了这个，固定了那个
Dialogue: 1,0:17:07.17,0:17:10.95,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}which then gives us this to force that and that's sort of just an add-on
Dialogue: 0,0:17:07.17,0:17:10.95,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这就让我们确定了这个
Dialogue: 1,0:17:10.95,0:17:15.30,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}then those two which finally reveal where that final light bulb in this row has to go
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.95,0:17:15.30,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然后是这两个，这就最终揭示了这排我们需要放置的最后那个灯泡
Dialogue: 1,0:17:15.30,0:17:16.07,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}which is there
Dialogue: 0,0:17:15.30,0:17:16.07,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}就是那里
Dialogue: 1,0:17:16.07,0:17:19.27,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, most of our solution path is intact
Dialogue: 0,0:17:16.07,0:17:19.27,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，我们的解法的大部分路径都是完整的
Dialogue: 1,0:17:19.27,0:17:22.28,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}there's maybe a few places where we could skip ahead a little bit
Dialogue: 0,0:17:19.27,0:17:22.28,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}也许有几个地方我们可以跳过去一点儿
Dialogue: 1,0:17:22.28,0:17:24.71,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}do we want to go back back and fix it
Dialogue: 0,0:17:22.28,0:17:24.71,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我们需要回去修复它吗？
Dialogue: 1,0:17:24.71,0:17:29.83,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}we could if we were really trying to go for a specific uh look or a specific theme
Dialogue: 0,0:17:24.71,0:17:29.83,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我们可以这么做，如果我们真的是想追求一个特定的形式或主题的话
Dialogue: 1,0:17:29.83,0:17:33.80,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but the point is you have a lot of freedom as a puzzle designer to create that
Dialogue: 0,0:17:29.83,0:17:33.80,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但关键点还是，作为一个谜题设计师，你有很大的自由来创造这些东西
Dialogue: 1,0:17:33.80,0:17:42.57,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and this method of designing from the front or forward design allows you to really have quite tight control over the solution experience of the person solving the puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.80,0:17:42.57,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这种从正面设计的方法，或者说前向设计，可以让你对解谜者的解谜体验有严格的控制
Dialogue: 1,0:17:42.57,0:17:46.41,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh if you do it correctly and if you're good at it which is is hard right
Dialogue: 0,0:17:42.57,0:17:46.41,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}前提是你做得对或者你很擅长这一点的话。但这很难，对嘛？
Dialogue: 1,0:17:46.41,0:17:49.41,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like i've been doing this for many years so I have some experience with this
Dialogue: 0,0:17:46.41,0:17:49.41,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}比如说，我已经做了很多年了，所以我会有些经验
Dialogue: 1,0:17:49.41,0:17:59.46,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and you know i have a sense of like where it could go wrong or what types of assumptions i should and shouldn't make when i'm making these sort of you know when i'm adding a new square to the grid
Dialogue: 0,0:17:49.41,0:17:59.46,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}当我在网格中添加东西时，我会对哪里可能出错、我应不应该做出什么样的假设有一定的感觉
Dialogue: 1,0:17:59.46,0:18:04.13,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}how is this going to affect the solution path based on what i've created so far
Dialogue: 0,0:17:59.46,0:18:04.13,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}以及基于我目前所创造的东西，这将如何影响解谜路径？
Dialogue: 1,0:18:04.13,0:18:08.49,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and you have to have a good sense of how these puzzles solve in order to be able to do that
Dialogue: 0,0:18:04.13,0:18:08.49,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你得对这些谜题的解法有一个很好的感觉，才能做到这一点
Dialogue: 1,0:18:08.49,0:18:12.52,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, some of the best composers of these puzzles are also the best solvers of them
Dialogue: 0,0:18:08.49,0:18:12.52,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，一些最好的谜题创作者也是最好的解谜者
Dialogue: 1,0:18:12.52,0:18:20.26,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because they themselves are able to once they place one thing in the grid they can deduce exactly all that can be deduced from it
Dialogue: 0,0:18:12.52,0:18:20.26,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为一旦他们自己在网格中添加什么东西，他们就能准确推导出所有能被推导出的东西
Dialogue: 1,0:18:20.26,0:18:24.29,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and therefore, have a really good understanding of what the solver experience is going to be
Dialogue: 0,0:18:20.26,0:18:24.29,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因此他们也就对解题者的体验有很好的了解
Dialogue: 1,0:18:24.29,0:18:26.66,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um with logic puzzles that's true
Dialogue: 0,0:18:24.29,0:18:26.66,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}对逻辑解谜来说是这样的
Dialogue: 1,0:18:26.66,0:18:29.73,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}although it's less true with other types of puzzles like crosswords um
Dialogue: 0,0:18:26.66,0:18:29.73,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}尽管对于其他类型的谜题，比如填字游戏，可能就不完全是这样了
Dialogue: 1,0:18:29.73,0:18:32.04,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I think there's a famous mike sellinger quote
Dialogue: 0,0:18:29.73,0:18:32.04,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我想Mike Sellinger曾经说过一句著名的话
Dialogue: 1,0:18:32.04,0:18:39.53,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}where he says um you know making a good crossword versus solving a crossword is is like arson versus firefighting
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.04,0:18:39.53,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}他说：“创作一个好的填字游戏之于解填字游戏，就如同纵火之于救火”
Dialogue: 1,0:18:39.53,0:18:47.85,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and it's not necessary that the same person is going to be it's not necessarily true that the same person is going to be good at both arson and firefighting
Dialogue: 0,0:18:39.53,0:18:47.85,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}同一个人不一定就得同时擅长纵火和救火
Dialogue: 1,0:18:47.85,0:18:51.94,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but with logic puzzles I think it often is
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.85,0:18:51.94,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但对于逻辑谜题来说，我认为大部分情况是这样的
Dialogue: 1,0:18:51.94,0:18:57.38,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}anyways I’m going to close this don't need to save it
Dialogue: 0,0:18:51.94,0:18:57.38,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}无论如何，我要把这个给关了，不需要保存
Dialogue: 1,0:18:57.38,0:19:00.97,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, designing from the front has a number of benefits
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.38,0:19:00.97,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，从正面设计有很多好处
Dialogue: 1,0:19:00.97,0:19:03.14,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh you know you can control the flow
Dialogue: 0,0:19:00.97,0:19:03.14,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你知道你可以控制解谜流程
Dialogue: 1,0:19:03.14,0:19:05.19,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you can create these playful setups
Dialogue: 0,0:19:03.14,0:19:05.19,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你可以创造这些有趣的设置
Dialogue: 1,0:19:05.19,0:19:08.01,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and you can hide eureka moments in really interesting ways
Dialogue: 0,0:19:05.19,0:19:08.01,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你可以用非常有趣的方式来隐藏尤里卡时刻
Dialogue: 1,0:19:08.01,0:19:17.35,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}another thing that designing from the front enables is this sort of deductive solution where as a solver you're making logical deductions you're never guessing right
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.01,0:19:17.35,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}从正面设计带来的另一个好处是，作为解谜者，你在进行逻辑推理而不是在猜测，是吧？
Dialogue: 1,0:19:17.35,0:19:22.21,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like when you solve a sudoku you generally aren't guessing you're putting in a number once you're confident that that's true
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.35,0:19:22.21,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}就当你在解数独时，你一般不是在猜测，而是一旦你确信这是对的，就填入一个数字
Dialogue: 1,0:19:22.21,0:19:28.10,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and that means that once you get to the end and you found a unique solution you're sort of aware that it is unique
Dialogue: 0,0:19:22.21,0:19:28.10,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这意味着，一旦你走到了最后，你找到了个独特的解法，你会意识到它既是独特的
Dialogue: 1,0:19:28.10,0:19:31.94,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because in solving the puzzle deductively you have established that uniqueness
Dialogue: 0,0:19:28.10,0:19:31.94,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为在通过推理解谜的过程中，你已经建立起了这种唯一性
Dialogue: 1,0:19:31.94,0:19:34.25,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and this can be a source of pleasure as a solver
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.94,0:19:34.25,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而作为解谜者，这可能就是一个快乐的来源
Dialogue: 1,0:19:34.25,0:19:43.21,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because it's it's sort of like the soundness and completeness meeting together implying that both the existence and uniqueness of the puzzle have been established
Dialogue: 0,0:19:34.25,0:19:43.21,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为这类似于说，可靠性和完备性同时满足，就意味着谜题的存在性和独特性都被确立了
Dialogue: 1,0:19:43.21,0:19:50.12,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and that's different than a puzzle where you guess and you find the answer and you don't even know is this the unique answer is this the only answer
Dialogue: 0,0:19:43.21,0:19:50.12,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这与那种猜答案的谜题不同，那种谜题里面你找到了答案而你甚至不能确定是不是唯一的答案
Dialogue: 1,0:19:50.12,0:20:01.51,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you know this definitively is the unique answer and you had to find it by sort of going through the motions that were uh intended for you to go through
Dialogue: 0,0:19:50.12,0:20:01.51,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}（而这种谜题）是肯定有唯一答案的，因为你得通过一套规定动作来找到它
Dialogue: 1,0:20:01.51,0:20:09.06,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um and that is what enables this communication because you know that this is what the puzzle designer intended you to do when you're solving it
Dialogue: 0,0:20:01.51,0:20:09.06,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而这就是促成这种交流的原因，因为你知道这就是谜题设计者希望你在解题时做的事情
Dialogue: 1,0:20:09.06,0:20:11.11,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and you're consciously aware of that
Dialogue: 0,0:20:09.06,0:20:11.11,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而你也清楚地意识到这一点
Dialogue: 1,0:20:11.11,0:20:20.20,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and the the puzzle designer is surprising you with what the next step is and how it's been laid out and not just with the you know what the actual solution is
Dialogue: 0,0:20:11.11,0:20:20.20,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}谜题设计者通过下一步是什么和怎么布置的，而不只是用实际的解法是什么来带给你惊喜
Dialogue: 1,0:20:20.20,0:20:25.13,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}the the surprising thing at the end of the puzzle isn't what the final grid looks like when it's done
Dialogue: 0,0:20:20.20,0:20:25.13,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}在谜题的最后，令人惊喜的事情并不是最后的网格看起来是什么样子的
Dialogue: 1,0:20:25.13,0:20:30.37,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it's what was the logic that enabled you to deduce that that was the only way it could be
Dialogue: 0,0:20:25.13,0:20:30.37,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而是让你能推断出这是唯一方法的逻辑是什么
Dialogue: 1,0:20:30.37,0:20:38.50,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and that is is the thing that elevates these types of logic puzzles to a greater aesthetic than a computer generated sudoku
Dialogue: 0,0:20:30.37,0:20:38.50,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而这正是将这类逻辑谜题提升到比计算机生成的数独有更高的审美境界的原因所在
Dialogue: 1,0:20:38.50,0:20:45.67,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}one of the important things to do is make the key move or sort of the key step that you have to do provably unique
Dialogue: 0,0:20:38.50,0:20:45.67,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而你需要做的很重要的一点是，「让谜题的关键步骤可被证明是独一无二的」
Dialogue: 1,0:20:45.67,0:20:50.09,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}if we go back to that um chess puzzle by Sam Lloyd,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:45.67,0:20:50.09,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}让我们回到Sam Lloyd那个国际象棋谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:20:50.09,0:20:53.54,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}king e2 is the only way to achieve that mate in three
Dialogue: 0,0:20:50.09,0:20:53.54,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}其中王e2是实现三步内将杀的唯一途径（即王往左上方走一格）
Dialogue: 1,0:20:53.54,0:21:03.65,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and the fact that that's true kind of forces the puzzle uh the puzzle forces the solver to uncover the planned eureka moment that has been set up um
Dialogue: 0,0:20:53.54,0:21:03.65,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而这一事实，意味着这个谜题迫使解谜者去发现这一设定好的尤里卡时刻
Dialogue: 1,0:21:03.65,0:21:06.73,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and in chess you know sometimes there's different responses
Dialogue: 0,0:21:03.65,0:21:06.73,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}在实际下棋中，你知道对手可能会有不同的反应
Dialogue: 1,0:21:06.73,0:21:13.57,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like if the player goes king e2 uh the opponent playing black does not have to respond by queening the pawn
Dialogue: 0,0:21:06.73,0:21:13.57,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}比如说，如果白方王e2，那黑方不一定就会把兵升变为后
Dialogue: 1,0:21:13.57,0:21:17.73,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}the player the opponent can respond by just moving a bishop or doing something else right
Dialogue: 0,0:21:13.57,0:21:17.73,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}对方可以通过移动象或其他事情来回击，是吧？
Dialogue: 1,0:21:17.73,0:21:21.00,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and in all of those cases the player does have mate in three
Dialogue: 0,0:21:17.73,0:21:21.00,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}在所有这种情况下，肯定都可以三步内将杀对面
Dialogue: 1,0:21:21.00,0:21:26.18,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but the most interesting part of the puzzle is sort of what do you do against the most challenging response
Dialogue: 0,0:21:21.00,0:21:26.18,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但谜题最有趣的部分应该是你如何去应对最有挑战性的回击
Dialogue: 1,0:21:26.18,0:21:31.05,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and so, the fact that there's one key move on the first move is essential in all chess puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:21:26.18,0:21:31.05,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因此，第一步棋是关键步对所有国际象棋谜题来说都是必不可少的
Dialogue: 1,0:21:31.05,0:21:35.27,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it's sort of a requirement of the genre there needs to be a single unique key move on turn one
Dialogue: 0,0:21:31.05,0:21:35.27,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}第一步棋有一个独特的关键走法，算是这种类型谜题的要求
Dialogue: 1,0:21:35.27,0:21:41.16,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but then often in subsequent turns it can sort of fork and branch a little bit more depending on what the opponent does
Dialogue: 0,0:21:35.27,0:21:41.16,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但在随后的汇合中，就会根据对方的行动而出现分支
Dialogue: 1,0:21:41.16,0:21:45.25,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and it's not you know you need to kind of find a response to everything right
Dialogue: 0,0:21:41.16,0:21:45.25,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}对每一种对手的行动你都需要找到一种回应方式
Dialogue: 1,0:21:45.25,0:21:49.41,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, the fact that the later part of the puzzle may not be unique because of what the opponent can do
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.25,0:21:49.41,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，尽管谜题后半部分可能因为对手的下法，并不是独一无二的
Dialogue: 1,0:21:49.41,0:21:52.81,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}doesn't spoil the aesthetics of the puzzle having a unique key move
Dialogue: 0,0:21:49.41,0:21:52.81,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但这并不影响谜题拥有独一无二的关键一步的美感
Dialogue: 1,0:21:52.81,0:22:00.29,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}puzzles that lack a unique key move are often called “cooked puzzles” meaning you know as in “his goose is cooked”
Dialogue: 0,0:21:52.81,0:22:00.29,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}缺乏独一无二的关键步骤的谜题通常被称为”cooked puzzle”，来自”his goose is cooked”中的”cooked”
Dialogue: 1,0:22:00.29,0:22:03.75,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it's just like not a good puzzle or it's not worthy of being printed
Dialogue: 0,0:22:00.29,0:22:03.75,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这就意味着它不是一道好谜题，或者说它不值得印刷出来
Dialogue: 1,0:22:03.75,0:22:06.50,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}a second solution is often called a “dual”
Dialogue: 0,0:22:03.75,0:22:06.50,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}（谜题的）第二种解法通常被称为“Dual”
Dialogue: 1,0:22:06.50,0:22:09.77,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}or in video games I’ve heard it called an “exploit”
Dialogue: 0,0:22:06.50,0:22:09.77,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}或者在电子游戏中我听说这被叫做“exploit”（秘技/卡bug）
Dialogue: 1,0:22:09.77,0:22:19.49,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}where the player can get around the intended thing that the developer was trying to force them to do but the player is somehow able to find an exploit to avoid doing this
Dialogue: 0,0:22:09.77,0:22:19.49,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}也就是玩家通过找到了某种方式或漏洞，绕过了开发者试图强迫他们做的事情
Dialogue: 1,0:22:19.49,0:22:23.85,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and if the purpose of your puzzle is to conceal a unique eureka moment,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:19.49,0:22:23.85,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你的谜题的目的是为了隐藏一个独特的尤里卡时刻
Dialogue: 1,0:22:23.85,0:22:27.05,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}then intentionally having multiple solutions is not a good idea
Dialogue: 0,0:22:23.85,0:22:27.05,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}那么故意提供多种解法就不是一个好主意
Dialogue: 1,0:22:27.05,0:22:33.45,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and accidentally having multiple solutions may be a problem that you know you want your QA to catch
Dialogue: 0,0:22:27.05,0:22:33.45,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而意外地拥有多种解法，可能就是你希望你的测试人员能够发现的问题
Dialogue: 1,0:22:33.45,0:22:40.29,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}if you're doing puzzle design you want to make sure that your test solvers are really good at finding those multiple solutions
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.45,0:22:40.29,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你在做谜题设计，你要确保你的测试人员擅长找到那些多重解法
Dialogue: 1,0:22:40.29,0:22:47.91,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and the way you want them to do that is by being deductive solvers that can really try and establish the uniqueness of every solution by proving it
Dialogue: 0,0:22:40.29,0:22:47.91,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你想让他们做到，成为推理型的解题者，能够真正通过证明的方式来确定每个解的唯一性
Dialogue: 1,0:22:47.91,0:22:53.86,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um and that's hard for some types of puzzles especially uh very stateful puzzles like block pushing puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:22:47.91,0:22:53.86,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而这对于某些类型的谜题来说是很难的，尤其是像推箱子这种状态很多的谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:22:53.86,0:23:04.29,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}where there's a million different states that the puzzle can be in and it's often very hard to determine that an alternative way of solving the puzzle is impossible
Dialogue: 0,0:22:53.86,0:23:04.29,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}那里面有无数种不同的状态，通常很难确定出现另一种解法是不是不可能的
Dialogue: 1,0:23:04.29,0:23:08.01,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you really want to as a puzzle designer make sure you're slicing off those Rabbit Trails
Dialogue: 0,0:23:04.29,0:23:08.01,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}作为一个谜题设计者，你得确保你把那些Rabbit Trails给去除掉
Dialogue: 1,0:23:08.01,0:23:12.81,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and just making it so that you don't have to check too deep in order to make sure that something doesn't happen
Dialogue: 0,0:23:08.01,0:23:12.81,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这样你就不必为了确保某些事情不发生而检查得太深
Dialogue: 1,0:23:12.81,0:23:16.58,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I can give you a million examples of these which I didn't include in the talk
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.81,0:23:16.58,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我可以给你举出无数个例子，我之前没把这个包含在演讲里
Dialogue: 1,0:23:16.58,0:23:22.79,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I think the one that sticks with me the most is in steven's sausage roll they have this level called the tower
Dialogue: 0,0:23:16.58,0:23:22.79,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我想最让我印象深刻的例子是在《史蒂芬香肠卷》中，有个叫“The Tower”的关卡
Dialogue: 1,0:23:22.79,0:23:26.95,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}where there's eight sausages stacked up and you have to sort of set them up in this unique way
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.79,0:23:26.95,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}那里面有八个香肠堆在一起，而你得以一种特别的方式把它们摆好
Dialogue: 1,0:23:26.95,0:23:30.47,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um but the way I solved that puzzle was not the intended way
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.95,0:23:30.47,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但我解决这个谜题的方式并不是开发者设计的方式
Dialogue: 1,0:23:30.47,0:23:35.78,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and the way a number of people solved it I’ve checked on YouTube and twitch videos was really not the intended way
Dialogue: 0,0:23:30.47,0:23:35.78,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我看油管和Twitch上很多人也不是用的开发者设计的方式
Dialogue: 1,0:23:35.78,0:23:45.13,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um I mean they ultimately got to the same final state but the sort of setup or the way they went about going about the setup to get there uh can vary in a lot of ways
Dialogue: 0,0:23:35.78,0:23:45.13,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}他们最终是到达了相同的最终状态，但他们达成的方式却是不尽相同的
Dialogue: 1,0:23:45.13,0:23:53.25,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and some of the setups are really convoluted like the thing that I did was kind of really complex and annoying and difficult to set up and painful
Dialogue: 0,0:23:45.13,0:23:53.25,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}有些方法真的很复杂，就像我的方法，真的很复杂凡人，而且很难做到、很痛苦
Dialogue: 1,0:23:53.25,0:23:59.01,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}whereas there was a nice intended solution to the puzzle but I never even saw it during my first playthrough
Dialogue: 0,0:23:53.25,0:23:59.01,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而它本身开发者设计的是一个很好的解法，但在我玩的一周目中我甚至没见到过这种解法
Dialogue: 1,0:23:59.01,0:24:03.69,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I basically had to cheat and look up the answer before I learned what the intended solution was
Dialogue: 0,0:23:59.01,0:24:03.69,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我恐怕得通过作弊或者查找答案才能知道预定的解法是什么
Dialogue: 1,0:24:03.69,0:24:12.90,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and I think my experience playing that game would have been a lot better if I had been coerced toward the intended solution more strongly
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.69,0:24:12.90,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我想，如果我被更有力地迫使去寻找预定解法的话，我玩这个游戏的体验会好很多
Dialogue: 1,0:24:12.90,0:24:19.24,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}anyways like deductive puzzles kind of need to have unique solutions
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.90,0:24:19.24,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}总之，逻辑推理型的谜题还是需要有独一无二的解法的
Dialogue: 1,0:24:19.24,0:24:25.51,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because the flow demands that you sort of prove every step you're not guessing right
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.24,0:24:25.51,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为解谜的流程就要求你去证明每一步，毕竟你不是在猜测，是吧？
Dialogue: 1,0:24:25.51,0:24:30.89,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so you need to be able to prove every step that you move forward on and therefore you have to just end up with one solution at the end
Dialogue: 0,0:24:25.51,0:24:30.89,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以你每前进一步都需要做出证明，因此必须在最后只得到一个解法
Dialogue: 1,0:24:30.89,0:24:35.11,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you wouldn't be able to have deductive flow if the solution wasn't unique
Dialogue: 0,0:24:30.89,0:24:35.11,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果解法不唯一的话，你就不可能有一个演绎推理的思维流
Dialogue: 1,0:24:35.11,0:24:39.78,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um so many types of puzzles chess puzzles logic puzzles etc. demand solutions
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.11,0:24:39.78,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，许多类型的谜题，如象棋棋谜，逻辑谜题等，都需要（独一无二的）解法
Dialogue: 1,0:24:39.78,0:24:43.69,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but many other types of puzzles ought to have unique solutions
Dialogue: 0,0:24:39.78,0:24:43.69,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但是许多其他类型的谜题也应该有唯一的解法
Dialogue: 1,0:24:43.69,0:24:48.74,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because of the aesthetics and because of the need to have a unique eureka moment and to force that on the player
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.69,0:24:48.74,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为需要一个独特的尤里卡时刻并将其带给玩家
Dialogue: 1,0:24:48.74,0:24:51.11,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}unique solutions are just a way to facilitate that
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.74,0:24:51.11,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}唯一的解法正是促进这一目标的一种方式
Dialogue: 1,0:24:51.11,0:24:54.18,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, I advocate uniqueness whenever somebody asks me
Dialogue: 0,0:24:51.11,0:24:54.18,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，每当有人问我，我都主张解法要有唯一性
Dialogue: 1,0:24:54.18,0:24:58.28,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you know and for those point-and-click adventure games that have multiple solutions to some puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:24:54.18,0:24:58.28,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你知道，对于那些其中谜题有多种解法的点击冒险游戏来说
Dialogue: 1,0:24:58.28,0:25:00.90,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}that can be okay like
Dialogue: 0,0:24:58.28,0:25:00.90,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}（有多种解法）可能问题不大
Dialogue: 1,0:25:00.90,0:25:05.70,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}there are there are many downsides right like you're doing extra work that the player might not even see
Dialogue: 0,0:25:00.90,0:25:05.70,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但也有很多坏处，比如你是在做一些玩家可能根本看不到的无用功
Dialogue: 1,0:25:05.70,0:25:09.99,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um sometimes you'll end up with an extra item and not even know what it was for
Dialogue: 0,0:25:05.70,0:25:09.99,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}有时你在游戏中会得到一个额外的物品，但你甚至不知道它是用来做什么的
Dialogue: 1,0:25:09.99,0:25:16.52,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um you know like oh that was for the second possible solution to that puzzle and you never used it
Dialogue: 0,0:25:09.99,0:25:16.52,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你知道，那是给那个谜题的第二种解法用的，但你从来没有用过它
Dialogue: 1,0:25:16.52,0:25:20.61,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like you want to have this feeling of every item in the game having had a purpose right
Dialogue: 0,0:25:16.52,0:25:20.61,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你会想有这样的感觉，游戏中的每件物品都应该有一个用途，对吗？
Dialogue: 1,0:25:20.61,0:25:22.47,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like I got that thing what was it for um
Dialogue: 0,0:25:20.61,0:25:22.47,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}就比如我得到了那个东西，那它有什么用呢？
Dialogue: 1,0:25:22.47,0:25:26.44,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}if you leave the game without feeling that you understood that purpose
Dialogue: 0,0:25:22.47,0:25:26.44,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你在离开游戏时，没有感觉到你理解了那个物品的用途
Dialogue: 1,0:25:26.44,0:25:32.84,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}then sometimes it can feel a little incomplete or it feels like you know the communication was lost at some point um
Dialogue: 0,0:25:26.44,0:25:32.84,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}那有时就会感觉到有点不完整，或者就像感觉从某一刻起你失去了与开发者之间的交流
Dialogue: 1,0:25:32.84,0:25:37.77,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you know so there's a lot to think about with regards to uniqueness
Dialogue: 0,0:25:32.84,0:25:37.77,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以关于唯一性的问题还是有很多东西需要思考的
Dialogue: 1,0:25:37.77,0:25:41.09,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}moving on let's talk about themes
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.77,0:25:41.09,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}继续下一课，我们来谈一谈“主题”
Dialogue: 1,0:25:41.09,0:25:46.09,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}adding a theme to puzzles can bring value in many different ways
Dialogue: 0,0:25:41.09,0:25:46.09,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}为谜题添加一个主题可以在很多方面带来价值
Dialogue: 1,0:25:46.09,0:25:51.14,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}one example that I will give are burr puzzles or kumiki puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:25:46.09,0:25:51.14,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我举一个例子，就是一般的孔明锁（Burr Puzzle）和“組木”（Kumiki Puzzle）
Dialogue: 1,0:25:51.14,0:25:54.60,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}kumiki puzzles are Japanese animal themed burr puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:25:51.14,0:25:54.60,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}組木 是日本的以动物为主题的孔明锁
Dialogue: 1,0:25:54.60,0:25:55.94,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I have one right here
Dialogue: 0,0:25:54.60,0:25:55.94,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我这里就有一个
Dialogue: 1,0:25:55.94,0:25:58.89,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}this is sort of themed as a pig
Dialogue: 0,0:25:55.94,0:25:58.89,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这个是以猪为主题的
Dialogue: 1,0:25:58.89,0:26:01.51,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh I can show you too it's a cool puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:25:58.89,0:26:01.51,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我给你看看，这是一个很酷的谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:26:01.51,0:26:03.43,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it's cute it's not particularly difficult
Dialogue: 0,0:26:01.51,0:26:03.43,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}很可爱，也不是特别难
Dialogue: 1,0:26:03.43,0:26:05.86,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but it has this move where you have to press the nose in
Dialogue: 0,0:26:03.43,0:26:05.86,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但它有个操作，你必须得把鼻子按进去
Dialogue: 1,0:26:05.86,0:26:09.96,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and then that's what's required to sort of get out the first piece uh
Dialogue: 0,0:26:05.86,0:26:09.96,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然后才能取出第一块组件
Dialogue: 1,0:26:09.96,0:26:13.99,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you press the nose in and it's just kind of quaint and clever
Dialogue: 0,0:26:09.96,0:26:13.99,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你得把鼻子按进去，这设计得很巧妙、聪明
Dialogue: 1,0:26:13.99,0:26:22.44,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um as opposed to just a regular old burr puzzle which is uh you know just a bunch of wooden sticks that you have to notch together
Dialogue: 0,0:26:13.99,0:26:22.44,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而左边普通的孔明锁，相比较起来就是一堆木棍，你得把它们拼合在一起
Dialogue: 1,0:26:22.44,0:26:24.23,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}there's something a little bit more
Dialogue: 0,0:26:22.44,0:26:24.23,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}右边的谜题有些更多的东西
Dialogue: 1,0:26:24.23,0:26:27.94,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and uh it can also help you kind of remember what you're doing
Dialogue: 0,0:26:24.23,0:26:27.94,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而且它还能帮助你记住正在做什么
Dialogue: 1,0:26:27.94,0:26:31.91,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like when you have the pieces laid out on the table and you're trying to put this thing back together
Dialogue: 0,0:26:27.94,0:26:31.91,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}比如说你把所有的组件放在桌子上，你想把这个东西拼起来的时候
Dialogue: 1,0:26:31.91,0:26:35.11,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um you realize well okay that's the ears that's the legs
Dialogue: 0,0:26:31.91,0:26:35.11,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你会意识到，好吧，那个是耳朵，那个是腿
Dialogue: 1,0:26:35.11,0:26:44.90,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}that's the you know the language of where things go and how things fit together uh can somehow uh be easier if the theme is there
Dialogue: 0,0:26:35.11,0:26:44.90,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果有主题的话，就会形成关于这个谜题的语言，拼起来也更简单一下
Dialogue: 1,0:26:44.90,0:26:48.23,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh I’ll show you a couple of other examples these are slitherlinks
Dialogue: 0,0:26:44.90,0:26:48.23,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我给你看几个其他的例子，这些是数回谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:26:48.23,0:26:57.89,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}on the left is one by Serkan Yürekli and this was done for the Indian national puzzle championship uh maybe like six seven years ago
Dialogue: 0,0:26:48.23,0:26:57.89,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}左边这个是Serkan Yürekli为印度全国谜题锦标赛设计的，大概6、7年前做的
Dialogue: 1,0:26:57.89,0:27:04.81,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it's done in the theme of I’m not sure if it's a lily pad or a lotus flower or some kind of uh elaborate geometric design
Dialogue: 0,0:26:57.89,0:27:04.81,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}它的主题是...... 我不确定这是睡莲还是莲花，或者是某种精心设计的几何图形
Dialogue: 1,0:27:04.81,0:27:08.45,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but that design actually makes the slitherlinks puzzle more interesting
Dialogue: 0,0:27:04.81,0:27:08.45,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但这一设计实际上使得数回谜题更有趣
Dialogue: 1,0:27:08.45,0:27:16.45,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like there is a vertex of degree 17 in the middle of this puzzle which you know you never see in a normal uh slither link with square geometry
Dialogue: 0,0:27:08.45,0:27:16.45,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}比如这个谜题中间有个17度的顶点，在普通方形的数回谜题中是看不到的
Dialogue: 1,0:27:16.45,0:27:24.71,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and sort of these two twos over here and the way they uh relate to this degree high degree vertex in the middle that's actually the break into this puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:27:16.45,0:27:24.71,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而这里的两个2，它们如何与中间这个点的度数相关的，正是这个谜题的突破点
Dialogue: 1,0:27:24.71,0:27:29.38,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}the essential part of the solution is to kind of work out how that might function
Dialogue: 0,0:27:24.71,0:27:29.38,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而这个谜题最关键的点就是找出这部分是如何起作用的
Dialogue: 1,0:27:29.38,0:27:37.00,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um and so it's not just aesthetic for the sake of aesthetics it also lends itself to the solution the puzzle which is amazing
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.38,0:27:37.00,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以这不仅仅为了美学的目的，这也支持着这个谜题的解，这很了不起
Dialogue: 1,0:27:37.00,0:27:40.97,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}the one on the right is a slitherlink puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:27:37.00,0:27:40.97,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}右边这个也是一个数回谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:27:40.97,0:27:51.46,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}where the 0,1,2, and 3 numbers have been replaced by the four letters M, O, A, Y in some order
Dialogue: 0,0:27:40.97,0:27:51.46,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}0,1,2,3这几个数字被M,O,A,Y这四个字母按一定顺序取代了
Dialogue: 1,0:27:51.46,0:27:54.21,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and figuring out that order is part of the puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:27:51.46,0:27:54.21,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而弄清这个顺序也是谜题的一部分
Dialogue: 1,0:27:54.21,0:27:58.76,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um and this was also published on Mother’s Day on grandmaster puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:27:54.21,0:27:58.76,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这个谜题是在母亲节那天发表在Grandmaster Puzzles上的
Dialogue: 1,0:27:58.76,0:28:05.54,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and it has the words mama mommy you know in in in a bunch of uh corners of the grid
Dialogue: 0,0:27:58.76,0:28:05.54,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}上面有“MAMA”“MOMMY”的字样，在角落里
Dialogue: 1,0:28:05.54,0:28:10.28,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you know mama is there like it's just kind of cute and clever and interesting
Dialogue: 0,0:28:05.54,0:28:10.28,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这是一种有点可爱、聪明、有趣的设计
Dialogue: 1,0:28:10.28,0:28:12.33,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but it's also a valid slitherlink
Dialogue: 0,0:28:10.28,0:28:12.33,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但它也是一个有效的数回谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:28:12.33,0:28:18.53,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh and you know it just adds some little bit of extra sparkle or spice to this puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:28:12.33,0:28:18.53,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这就给谜题带来了些额外的Sparkle和趣味
Dialogue: 1,0:28:18.53,0:28:22.82,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um another benefit is like when you're creating these puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:28:18.53,0:28:22.82,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}另一个好处是，当你创作谜题的时候
Dialogue: 1,0:28:22.82,0:28:26.85,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}sometimes you know it's like a blank page you don't know what to do what you want to create
Dialogue: 0,0:28:22.82,0:28:26.85,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}有时你就像拿出了一张白纸，你不知道该做什么，你想创造什么
Dialogue: 1,0:28:26.85,0:28:32.93,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and coming up with a good theme can lead you in the direction of uh concretizing your ideas
Dialogue: 0,0:28:26.85,0:28:32.93,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而想出一个好的主题可以引导你把你的想法具体化
Dialogue: 1,0:28:32.93,0:28:37.86,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and having some kind of uh you know key thing to frame your puzzle around
Dialogue: 0,0:28:32.93,0:28:37.86,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}以及给你一些你可以围绕着表达的关键点
Dialogue: 1,0:28:37.86,0:28:41.06,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like themes allow you to have a purpose to your puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:28:37.86,0:28:41.06,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}就像说主题可以让你的谜题有一个目的
Dialogue: 1,0:28:41.06,0:28:50.47,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}beyond just you know make one more of the same type of logic puzzle or crossword puzzle or you know wood puzzle whatever it is you're making
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.06,0:28:50.47,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而不仅仅是做一个相同类型的逻辑谜题或填字游戏或木制谜题之类的
Dialogue: 1,0:28:50.47,0:28:56.49,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, you get this additional aesthetic value but it's also useful as a constructor to be able to have them
Dialogue: 0,0:28:50.47,0:28:56.49,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，你得到了额外的美学价值，但作为创作者，拥有主题（对构造谜题）也是很有用的
Dialogue: 1,0:28:56.49,0:28:58.92,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it also makes the puzzles more memorable
Dialogue: 0,0:28:56.49,0:28:58.92,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}它也让谜题更容易被记住
Dialogue: 1,0:28:58.92,0:29:04.04,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because you know everybody knows oh that like 17 degrees slitherlink or that mother's day puzzle right
Dialogue: 0,0:28:58.92,0:29:04.04,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为，比如说，每个人都能记得那个17度的数回或那个母亲节的谜题，对吗？
Dialogue: 1,0:29:04.04,0:29:12.22,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it uh gives a short description to the puzzle and allows it to have a place in your brain where it sort of sticks out
Dialogue: 0,0:29:04.04,0:29:12.22,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}它为谜题提供了一个简短的描述，让它在你的大脑中占有一席之地，让它变得更加突出
Dialogue: 1,0:29:12.22,0:29:17.92,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}the converse to that is "don't be clever in ways that the solver will never notice"
Dialogue: 0,0:29:12.22,0:29:17.92,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而与之相反的是「不要在解谜者注意不到的地方耍小聪明」
Dialogue: 1,0:29:17.92,0:29:25.53,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh there are some themes that people think of as an idea for a crossword that uh maybe make the crossword worse
Dialogue: 0,0:29:17.92,0:29:25.53,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}有一些人们可能认为是填字游戏的主题，可能实际上会让谜题变得更糟
Dialogue: 1,0:29:25.53,0:29:27.32,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}here's a crossword
Dialogue: 0,0:29:25.53,0:29:27.32,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这里有个填字游戏
Dialogue: 1,0:29:27.32,0:29:30.20,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh it's actually quite a remarkable construction
Dialogue: 0,0:29:27.32,0:29:30.20,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这实际上是个很了不起的构造
Dialogue: 1,0:29:30.20,0:29:37.69,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it is a quintuple pangram meaning every letter of the alphabet from a to z has been used five times in this grid
Dialogue: 0,0:29:30.20,0:29:37.69,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这是一个“Quintuple Pangram”，意思是从A到Z每个字母都正好用了5次
Dialogue: 1,0:29:37.69,0:29:46.33,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, you will notice there are five Q’s in the grid there are five X’s and there are five Z’s and five J's and so on like
Dialogue: 0,0:29:37.69,0:29:46.33,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，你会注意到网格中有五个Q，五个X，五个Z，五个J，等等
Dialogue: 1,0:29:46.33,0:29:52.03,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so really uh the constructor here had to get in a lot of interesting words
Dialogue: 0,0:29:46.33,0:29:52.03,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，创作者必须得在这里面加入很多有趣的词语
Dialogue: 1,0:29:52.03,0:29:56.38,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you could see like so five Qs means there are ten keywords in this uh crossword
Dialogue: 0,0:29:52.03,0:29:56.38,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你可以看到五个Q意味着这个字谜里有十个关键词里有Q
Dialogue: 1,0:29:56.38,0:29:58.56,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because they are both across and down um
Dialogue: 0,0:29:56.38,0:29:58.56,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为既有横着的也有竖着的
Dialogue: 1,0:29:58.56,0:30:01.50,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, you know there's barbecue and square feet and quirk
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.56,0:30:01.50,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以你知道，这里有Barbecue（烤肉）、SQFT（square feet平方英尺）
Dialogue: 1,0:30:01.50,0:30:04.51,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and quack and quintuple and
Dialogue: 0,0:30:01.50,0:30:04.51,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}Quirk（怪癖）、Quack（呱呱叫）、Quintuple（五元组）
Dialogue: 1,0:30:04.51,0:30:07.84,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}quick and downquark uh q-tip right
Dialogue: 0,0:30:04.51,0:30:07.84,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}Quick（快）、Downquark（下夸克）、Q-TIP
Dialogue: 1,0:30:07.84,0:30:11.80,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, a lot of interesting and flavorful q words
Dialogue: 0,0:30:07.84,0:30:11.80,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，有很多有趣的有意思的含q的词
Dialogue: 1,0:30:11.80,0:30:16.03,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but there's also some words that are kind of not that great that that you wouldn't want in a crossword
Dialogue: 0,0:30:11.80,0:30:16.03,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但也有一些词不是很好，是那种你不会想在填字游戏中出现的词
Dialogue: 1,0:30:16.03,0:30:20.00,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}there's dxix for example like what is that
Dialogue: 0,0:30:16.03,0:30:20.00,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}比如说DXIX，那是什么？
Dialogue: 1,0:30:20.00,0:30:22.30,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I will show you in a moment um let's
Dialogue: 0,0:30:20.00,0:30:22.30,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我待会给你们看
Dialogue: 1,0:30:22.30,0:30:27.23,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I’ll share this quote with you which is from the late Nancy Salomon who passed away just a couple of months ago
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.30,0:30:27.23,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我和你们分享下这段话，这来自已故的Nancy Salomon，她在几个月前刚刚去世
Dialogue: 2,0:30:27.23,0:30:34.46,Annote,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}（译者注：Sage Advice这篇博客可以在cruciverb.com上搜索到，这是供新手填字游戏创作者学习的一篇文章）
Dialogue: 1,0:30:27.23,0:30:34.46,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}she is a godmother to all crossword creators with her famous sage advice uh blog um
Dialogue: 0,0:30:27.23,0:30:34.46,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}她是所有填字游戏创作者的教母，有这样一篇著名的叫“Sage Advice”的博客
Dialogue: 2,0:30:34.46,0:30:42.97,Annote,,0,0,0,,{\pos(995,910)\fad(120,120)}（译者注：这句话我个人是这么理解的，如果有误还望指正）
Dialogue: 1,0:30:34.46,0:30:42.97,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you know she shares that "a plethora of X’s, Z’s, Q’s, J’s and the like will buy you nothing but rejections if you pay too high a price for them."
Dialogue: 0,0:30:34.46,0:30:42.97,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}她分享说： \N “如果你为过多的X、Z、Q、J单词付出太多的代价，这只会让你的填字游戏被出版商退稿”
Dialogue: 1,0:30:42.97,0:30:45.92,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and so, here's a couple of examples
Dialogue: 0,0:30:42.97,0:30:45.92,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，这里面有这么几个例子
Dialogue: 2,0:30:45.92,0:30:51.80,Annote,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}（译者注：Albuquerque 阿尔伯克基/阿尔布开克/阿布奎基，是新墨西哥州最大的城市）
Dialogue: 1,0:30:45.92,0:30:49.37,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}one clue is Albuquerque’s home and the answer is NMEX
Dialogue: 0,0:30:45.92,0:30:49.37,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}一个谜面是“阿尔伯克基的所在地”，答案是NMEX
Dialogue: 1,0:30:49.37,0:30:51.80,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like it's supposed to be the state of New Mexico
Dialogue: 0,0:30:49.37,0:30:51.80,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这个答案本来应该是 新墨西哥州（New Mexico）
Dialogue: 1,0:30:51.80,0:30:56.35,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but who writes NMEX for New Mexico, like you might write NM
Dialogue: 0,0:30:51.80,0:30:56.35,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但谁会把新墨西哥州缩写成NMEX，最多也就写成NM
Dialogue: 1,0:30:56.35,0:31:01.98,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh this is kind of a weird abbreviation that feels kind of off and wrong
Dialogue: 0,0:30:56.35,0:31:01.98,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这是一种奇怪的缩写，感觉有点不对、不太行
Dialogue: 1,0:31:01.98,0:31:05.18,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and is that really the answer you want in your crossword?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:01.98,0:31:05.18,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这真的是你在填字游戏中想要的答案吗？
Dialogue: 1,0:31:05.18,0:31:10.81,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you know the DXIX is 519 in old Rome it is a Roman numeral clue
Dialogue: 0,0:31:05.18,0:31:10.81,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而DXIX则是罗马数字的519，这是个罗马数字的线索
Dialogue: 1,0:31:10.81,0:31:16.89,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and let me tell you that the number of times you've seen these if you've been doing crosswords long enough it always elicits a groan
Dialogue: 0,0:31:10.81,0:31:16.89,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}让我告诉你，如果你玩填字游戏的时间够久，每次见到这种线索，总会引起一声叹息
Dialogue: 1,0:31:16.89,0:31:26.17,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and it's always like well I guess if you had to if you really had to but like putting numbers in a crossword grid is kind of
Dialogue: 0,0:31:16.89,0:31:26.17,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我想如果你真的不得不这么做…但把数字放到填字游戏里有点…
Dialogue: 1,0:31:26.17,0:31:28.80,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you know once you've seen it once, you've seen it
Dialogue: 0,0:31:26.17,0:31:28.80,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你懂得，一旦你见过一次，你也就见过了
Dialogue: 1,0:31:28.80,0:31:40.38,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and like the point is you're paying sort of in the sparkle and the liveliness of the clues and the quality of the fill uh in order to achieve this goal of a quintuple pangram
Dialogue: 0,0:31:28.80,0:31:40.38,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}重点是，你为了达到每个字母用五次的目标，你牺牲了谜题的闪光点、生动性和质量
Dialogue: 1,0:31:40.38,0:31:45.63,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, the question is like you know what is what are you willing to do for your art right?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:40.38,0:31:45.63,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，问题是，为了艺术性你愿意付出什么？
Dialogue: 1,0:31:45.63,0:31:52.35,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and are you making this as something that is designed to be pleasurable for the solver or are you making this as a work of art
Dialogue: 0,0:31:45.63,0:31:52.35,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你是为了让解谜者感到愉悦，还是把它当作一件艺术品来做？
Dialogue: 1,0:31:52.35,0:31:55.68,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}maybe if you're making this as a work of art then it's worth it
Dialogue: 0,0:31:52.35,0:31:55.68,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你把它作为一件艺术作品，那么它就值得
Dialogue: 1,0:31:55.68,0:32:03.87,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but if your goal is to make it as something that's pleasurable for the solver then you've got to be a little bit careful
Dialogue: 0,0:31:55.68,0:32:03.87,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但如果你的目标是让解谜者感到愉悦，那你就得小心一点了
Dialogue: 1,0:32:03.87,0:32:08.35,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}this puzzle is by David C. Duncan Dekker and it is a remarkable puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:32:03.87,0:32:08.35,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这道谜题的作者是David C. Duncan Dekker，而这是一道了不起的谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:32:08.35,0:32:15.39,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and I think that as far as a quintuple pangram goes it's not that bad like there's actually some good words in here
Dialogue: 0,0:32:08.35,0:32:15.39,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我认为就每个字母用五次这种谜题而言，它并没有那么糟糕，这里面还是有些好词的
Dialogue: 1,0:32:15.39,0:32:21.79,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it's mostly lively fill there's not too many like really tenuous ones
Dialogue: 0,0:32:15.39,0:32:21.79,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}大部分都是充满生动性的词，没有太多浅薄的词
Dialogue: 1,0:32:21.79,0:32:26.08,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but there are some and it's just unavoidable when you're trying to achieve a goal this lofty
Dialogue: 0,0:32:21.79,0:32:26.08,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但总还是有一些的，而这是当你想实现如此高的目标时所难以避免的
Dialogue: 1,0:32:26.08,0:32:32.60,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I can think of all the puzzles that I’ve like wasted hours and hours trying to finish
Dialogue: 0,0:32:26.08,0:32:32.60,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我回想我那些浪费了很多时间来尝试创作的谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:32:32.60,0:32:38.62,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it was because I was trying to achieve some kind of aesthetic goal that was just not cooperating
Dialogue: 0,0:32:32.60,0:32:38.62,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}那都是因为我试图达到某种美学目标，但却难以与其他方面配合到一起
Dialogue: 1,0:32:38.62,0:32:40.99,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and I tried one thing and it didn't work tried another thing didn't work
Dialogue: 0,0:32:38.62,0:32:40.99,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我试了一件事，但没有成功，又试了另一件事也没有成功
Dialogue: 1,0:32:40.99,0:32:48.86,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and constantly having to back out and a lesson hard learned is to not make your goals too difficult
Dialogue: 0,0:32:40.99,0:32:48.86,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}只能一次次放弃，而我学到的一个惨痛教训是，不要让你的目标太难以实现
Dialogue: 1,0:32:48.86,0:32:53.47,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and especially not to compromise on the quality of the puzzle in order to achieve them
Dialogue: 0,0:32:48.86,0:32:53.47,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}尤其是不要为了实现这些目标而牺牲了谜题的质量
Dialogue: 1,0:32:53.47,0:32:58.14,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I will show you one more example this is the cast elk puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:32:53.47,0:32:58.14,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我再给你看一个例子，这是“Cast Elk”
Dialogue: 1,0:32:58.14,0:33:05.82,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}where is it I had it on my desk at some point is it on my shelf
Dialogue: 0,0:32:58.14,0:33:05.82,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}它放到哪里去了…它之前在我桌子上…在书架上吗
Dialogue: 1,0:33:05.82,0:33:09.53,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it's hiding my desk has a lot of stuff on it where is it
Dialogue: 0,0:33:05.82,0:33:09.53,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}它藏起来了…我桌子上有很多东西…它在哪里
Dialogue: 1,0:33:09.53,0:33:12.35,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}there it is okay uh here we go
Dialogue: 0,0:33:09.53,0:33:12.35,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}在这里，好吧
Dialogue: 1,0:33:12.35,0:33:16.70,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, this is a puzzle called the Cast Elk it's published by Hanayama
Dialogue: 0,0:33:12.35,0:33:16.70,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，这是一个由Hanayama发售的一个叫“Cast Elk”的谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:33:16.70,0:33:18.69,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh it's actually a really cool puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:33:16.70,0:33:18.69,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这其实是个非常酷的谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:33:18.69,0:33:30.27,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so, there's these two uh they're basically interlocked semicircular sort of c-shaped rings that are themed like a deer with antlers
Dialogue: 0,0:33:18.69,0:33:30.27,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}有这样两个扣起来的半圆形的，有点类似C形的环，是以带着鹿角的鹿为主题的
Dialogue: 1,0:33:30.27,0:33:32.25,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}or an elk I guess you know is what it's called
Dialogue: 0,0:33:30.27,0:33:32.25,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}或者说应该说是麋鹿，你知道它名字就是这么叫的
Dialogue: 1,0:33:32.25,0:33:38.65,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and you kind of have to slip them past each other and then sort of like rotate them sideways a bit and then they come apart
Dialogue: 0,0:33:32.25,0:33:38.65,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你必须把它滑过对方，然后把它们侧向旋转一下，然后它们就分开了
Dialogue: 1,0:33:38.65,0:33:42.69,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and you can reverse that to push them back together
Dialogue: 0,0:33:38.65,0:33:42.69,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你可以反着这个过程来把它们又扣起来
Dialogue: 1,0:33:42.69,0:33:50.11,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}the thing that's interesting about these is that well my spouse Alissa had this as a teenager
Dialogue: 0,0:33:42.69,0:33:50.11,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这里面有趣的是…我的配偶Alissa在十几岁时就有这个东西了
Dialogue: 1,0:33:50.11,0:33:55.81,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and she was able to solve the puzzle but she never actually noticed the trick
Dialogue: 0,0:33:50.11,0:33:55.81,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}她能够解决这个谜题，但她从来没有注意到其中的窍门
Dialogue: 1,0:33:55.81,0:34:02.46,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and the trick is that when you have these two things together um and you try to slip when you try to do this move
Dialogue: 0,0:33:55.81,0:34:02.46,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}诀窍是当这两部分扣起来时，当你试图做这个操作时
Dialogue: 1,0:34:02.46,0:34:04.96,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it actually most of the time will not work uh
Dialogue: 0,0:34:02.46,0:34:04.96,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}大多数情况下是不会成功的
Dialogue: 1,0:34:04.96,0:34:12.25,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and it's because these uh sort of tips of the antlers uh are not all the same length uh
Dialogue: 0,0:34:04.96,0:34:12.25,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这是因为这些鹿角的尖端并不都是一样长的
Dialogue: 1,0:34:12.25,0:34:16.80,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}there are two antler tips in this that are shorter than all of the rest
Dialogue: 0,0:34:12.25,0:34:16.80,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这里面有两个鹿角的尖端比其他的都要短
Dialogue: 1,0:34:16.80,0:34:21.73,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and when you have this interlock c-shape there's four kind of ways of taking it apart
Dialogue: 0,0:34:16.80,0:34:21.73,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}当这两个C型的部分互扣着的时候，有四种方式可以把它们拆开
Dialogue: 1,0:34:21.73,0:34:24.99,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}that seem like they're isometric but they're actually not
Dialogue: 0,0:34:21.73,0:34:24.99,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}看起来像是等距的，但实际上不是的
Dialogue: 1,0:34:24.99,0:34:28.06,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because the antlers are not the same length
Dialogue: 0,0:34:24.99,0:34:28.06,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为鹿角的长度是不一样的
Dialogue: 1,0:34:28.06,0:34:34.85,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so my spouse spent her teenage years not realizing why sometimes she could solve this puzzle and sometimes not
Dialogue: 0,0:34:28.06,0:34:34.85,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以我的配偶在她十几岁的时候并没有意识到为什么她有时能解开，有时又不能
Dialogue: 1,0:34:34.85,0:34:36.57,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and when you go to put it back together it's even worse
Dialogue: 0,0:34:34.85,0:34:36.57,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而当你把它拼起来的时候，情况就更糟糕了
Dialogue: 1,0:34:36.57,0:34:41.12,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because there's actually eight possible ways of putting it together only one of which works
Dialogue: 0,0:34:36.57,0:34:41.12,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为实际上有八种可能的组合方式，只有一种可行
Dialogue: 1,0:34:41.12,0:34:46.43,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um and so it's kind of like a cruel joke played by the puzzle designer
Dialogue: 0,0:34:41.12,0:34:46.43,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以这有点像谜题设计师开的一个残酷的玩笑
Dialogue: 1,0:34:46.43,0:34:49.76,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and if you're in on it it's great you know once you know the secret it seems clever
Dialogue: 0,0:34:46.43,0:34:49.76,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}一旦你知道了这个秘密就会觉得这看起来很聪明
Dialogue: 1,0:34:49.76,0:34:59.17,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but when you're solving it. it just seems kind of like a bit baffling and it can leave you with this feeling of like not really understanding what the intent of the puzzle designer was
Dialogue: 0,0:34:49.76,0:34:59.17,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但当你解开它的时候，就会觉得有点困惑，会让你感觉到不明白谜题设计者的意图是什么
Dialogue: 1,0:34:59.17,0:35:05.44,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um and so I think the lesson is that it would be great if after you solved this puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:34:59.17,0:35:05.44,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以我觉得，如果在你解开这个谜题后
Dialogue: 1,0:35:05.44,0:35:10.43,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you could sort of open a fortune cookie and learn by the way the secret is this um
Dialogue: 0,0:35:05.44,0:35:10.43,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你能够类似于打开幸运饼干，顺便了解一下这个秘密，那就还不错
Dialogue: 1,0:35:10.43,0:35:13.57,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because understanding that secret is sort of having the eureka moment
Dialogue: 0,0:35:10.43,0:35:13.57,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为理解了这个秘密，就有了尤里卡时刻
Dialogue: 1,0:35:13.57,0:35:16.13,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and if you solve the puzzle without having a eureka moment
Dialogue: 0,0:35:13.57,0:35:16.13,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你解开了这个谜题，却没有尤里卡的时刻
Dialogue: 1,0:35:16.13,0:35:20.48,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}then uh part of the aesthetic value of that puzzle is lost on you
Dialogue: 0,0:35:16.13,0:35:20.48,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}那么这个谜题的一部分美学价值就会消失了
Dialogue: 1,0:35:20.48,0:35:24.77,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and I can't count the number of times where I’ve watched somebody solve a video game puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:35:20.48,0:35:24.77,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我已经数不清有多少次看到有人解决一个电子游戏的谜题时
Dialogue: 1,0:35:24.77,0:35:30.27,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and they accidentally find the solution and move on and they're sort of missing out on the beauty that lies within that puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:35:24.77,0:35:30.27,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}他们是意外地找到了答案，然后就往前走了，他们就错过了那道谜题中美丽的部分
Dialogue: 1,0:35:30.27,0:35:33.47,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because they haven't discovered that the deeper secret lying within
Dialogue: 0,0:35:30.27,0:35:33.47,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为他们没有发现隐藏在其中的更深的秘密
Dialogue: 1,0:35:33.47,0:35:38.33,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and I mean many video game puzzles simply do not have a deeper secret lying within
Dialogue: 0,0:35:33.47,0:35:38.33,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}其实很多电子游戏根本就没有更深层次的秘密
Dialogue: 1,0:35:38.33,0:35:46.91,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but when they do I think you know my goal is always to allow the player to experience that deeper secret to let them in on the joke
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.33,0:35:46.91,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但如果有的话，我想我的目标是让玩家体验到更深层次的秘密
Dialogue: 1,0:35:46.91,0:35:49.53,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}to sort of maximize their exposure to the eureka moment
Dialogue: 0,0:35:46.91,0:35:49.53,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}去让他们最大限度地接触到尤里卡时刻
Dialogue: 1,0:35:49.53,0:35:54.91,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}even if it means telling them afterwards what is the thing that they were supposed to have figured out
Dialogue: 0,0:35:49.53,0:35:54.91,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}即使这意味着在事后告诉他们自己本应该发现的东西
Dialogue: 1,0:35:54.91,0:35:59.07,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because to me experiencing the eureka moment is the important part of the puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:35:54.91,0:35:59.07,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为对我来说，体验尤里卡时刻是谜题的重要部分
Dialogue: 1,0:35:59.07,0:36:00.86,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}now maybe you want to leave that secret in there
Dialogue: 0,0:35:59.07,0:36:00.86,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}或许你想把这个秘密留在那里
Dialogue: 1,0:36:00.86,0:36:03.17,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}maybe you want it to be something that somebody can come back to
Dialogue: 0,0:36:00.86,0:36:03.17,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}也许你想让它成为别人可以回味的东西
Dialogue: 1,0:36:03.17,0:36:05.09,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}maybe you want it to be you know a book
Dialogue: 0,0:36:03.17,0:36:05.09,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}也许你想让它成为那种，类似于一本书
Dialogue: 1,0:36:05.09,0:36:09.12,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}that when you read it the second time you learn a little bit more
Dialogue: 0,0:36:05.09,0:36:09.12,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}当你读第二遍的时候，你会学到一点更多的东西
Dialogue: 1,0:36:09.12,0:36:12.96,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}there's a little bit of depth that you can uncover in the second reading right
Dialogue: 0,0:36:09.12,0:36:12.96,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}有一些你能够在第二次阅读时发现的深度，对吗？
Dialogue: 1,0:36:12.96,0:36:15.97,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}that could be an option too but it's just something to think about
Dialogue: 0,0:36:12.96,0:36:15.97,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这也是一个选项，但这也得好好经过思考
Dialogue: 1,0:36:15.97,0:36:20.89,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and you know that's the end of this example I guess
Dialogue: 0,0:36:15.97,0:36:20.89,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}那么这个例子就到此为止了
Dialogue: 1,0:36:20.89,0:36:25.44,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}Next lesson is “the format changes everything”
Dialogue: 0,0:36:20.89,0:36:25.44,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}下一课是「形式会改变一切」
Dialogue: 1,0:36:25.44,0:36:30.30,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I want to show you a few examples of puzzles that are almost all the same
Dialogue: 0,0:36:25.44,0:36:30.30,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我给你们看几个例子，这些谜题几乎都一样
Dialogue: 1,0:36:30.30,0:36:38.49,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}these are all puzzles where you have to draw a path that sort of goes through everything on the grid
Dialogue: 0,0:36:30.30,0:36:38.49,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这些谜题都要求你必须画出穿过网格上所有东西的一条路径
Dialogue: 1,0:36:38.49,0:36:41.63,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and so, on this left this is a puzzle called simple loop
Dialogue: 0,0:36:38.49,0:36:41.63,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}左上角这个谜题叫《Simple Loop》
Dialogue: 1,0:36:41.63,0:36:48.48,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it's a paper-based logic puzzle you have to draw a loop that passes through every tile exactly once not including the shaded ones
Dialogue: 0,0:36:41.63,0:36:48.48,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这是一个纸质的逻辑解谜，你必须画一个环，经过每一个格子且只经过一次，不包括阴影部分
Dialogue: 1,0:36:48.48,0:36:52.51,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}this one on the bottom left is from a game called blossom tales
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.48,0:36:52.51,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}左下角这个谜题来自于一个叫《花之传说》（Blossom Tales）的游戏
Dialogue: 1,0:36:52.51,0:36:57.44,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and it's sort of the same puzzle except there's an entrance at the top and an exit at the bottom
Dialogue: 0,0:36:52.51,0:36:57.44,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}它也差不多是一样的谜题，只不过上面有一个入口，下面有一个出口
Dialogue: 1,0:36:57.44,0:37:01.73,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}this one in the middle is from the witness and it's the same except there's an entrance and an exit
Dialogue: 0,0:36:57.44,0:37:01.73,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}中间这个来自《见证者》，基本上也是一样的，除了有个入口和出口
Dialogue: 1,0:37:01.73,0:37:08.45,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and you only have to collect all the dots you don't actually have to visit sort of every vertex of the grid
Dialogue: 0,0:37:01.73,0:37:08.45,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而且只需要经过所有的点就行了，不用经过网格的每个顶点
Dialogue: 1,0:37:08.45,0:37:13.31,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}this one on the right has multiple entrances and exits and you may not know where they are
Dialogue: 0,0:37:08.45,0:37:13.31,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}右边这个有多个入口和出口，你可能不知道它们在哪里
Dialogue: 1,0:37:13.31,0:37:17.66,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}this is from a mobile puzzle game called alcazar
Dialogue: 0,0:37:13.31,0:37:17.66,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这是一个叫《Alcazar》的解谜手游
Dialogue: 1,0:37:17.66,0:37:19.71,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and it seems like they're all similar
Dialogue: 0,0:37:17.66,0:37:19.71,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}看起来它们都很相似
Dialogue: 1,0:37:19.71,0:37:24.96,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but there's actually a lot of differences in the solver experience when you're solving these puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:37:19.71,0:37:24.96,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但实际上当你解这些谜题时，体验有很大不同
Dialogue: 1,0:37:24.96,0:37:31.17,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um you know the modality of your input and the output that you're being shown right
Dialogue: 0,0:37:24.96,0:37:31.17,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}比如你的输入和输出显示的形式（不同）
Dialogue: 1,0:37:31.17,0:37:35.71,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}whether you're seeing a screen or seeing something physically in front of you or doing something on paper
Dialogue: 0,0:37:31.17,0:37:35.71,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}不论你看到的是屏幕，还是看到的实体的物品，或者说在纸上解谜
Dialogue: 1,0:37:35.71,0:37:39.74,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}whether you're using even controller versus keyboard mouse versus touch
Dialogue: 0,0:37:35.71,0:37:39.74,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}不论你用的是手柄还是键盘，鼠标还是触摸屏
Dialogue: 1,0:37:39.74,0:37:45.25,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}they all provide different affordances like can you click and drag do you have to move a cursor around to select which square you're on
Dialogue: 0,0:37:39.74,0:37:45.25,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}它们都提供了不同的能力，比如你能点击拖动吗，你需要移动光标来选择吗
Dialogue: 1,0:37:45.25,0:37:51.52,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}are you on a small screen or a big screen how big is the text of your puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:37:45.25,0:37:51.52,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}是在小屏幕还是大屏幕上，谜题的文字有多大
Dialogue: 1,0:37:51.52,0:37:54.65,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um can you undo and restart can you save your progress
Dialogue: 0,0:37:51.52,0:37:54.65,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}可以撤销和重启吗，可以保存进度吗
Dialogue: 1,0:37:54.65,0:37:56.96,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}on paper you have to literally use an eraser
Dialogue: 0,0:37:54.65,0:37:56.96,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}在纸上你需要用橡皮擦
Dialogue: 1,0:37:56.96,0:38:01.44,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but you can also use multiple colors of pencils to maybe make a guess and try something out
Dialogue: 0,0:37:56.96,0:38:01.44,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但你也可以用多种颜色的铅笔来做出猜测或者尝试
Dialogue: 1,0:38:01.44,0:38:08.99,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and then you know what you want to erase uh when you're uh done making that guess and decided that's not the way forward
Dialogue: 0,0:38:01.44,0:38:08.99,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}之后你就需要擦除一些东西
Dialogue: 1,0:38:08.99,0:38:13.79,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}some video games have undo systems where you can make a move and go back some don't
Dialogue: 0,0:38:08.99,0:38:13.79,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}有的电子游戏有撤销的操作，你可以做一个操作然后回到上一步，而有的游戏没有
Dialogue: 1,0:38:13.79,0:38:19.74,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}some are brutal blossom tales actually if you step off the path onto those red zones
Dialogue: 0,0:38:13.79,0:38:19.74,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}有的又很残酷，《花之传说》里面如果你走到红格子上了
Dialogue: 1,0:38:19.74,0:38:21.79,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you take damage and you have to restart
Dialogue: 0,0:38:19.74,0:38:21.79,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你会受到伤害，而且你必须重新开始
Dialogue: 1,0:38:21.79,0:38:27.29,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and there's no undo meaning that if you don't solve the puzzle correctly on the first try you actually are hurt
Dialogue: 0,0:38:21.79,0:38:27.29,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}没有撤销就意味着如果你一次没有做出正确尝试，你就会受到伤害
Dialogue: 1,0:38:27.29,0:38:33.57,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you know when I got to this puzzle I literally just print screened it and turned it into MS paint and solved it in there
Dialogue: 0,0:38:27.29,0:38:33.57,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}当时我解这个谜题的时候，我是截屏然后放到画图里面，先在里面把它解出来
Dialogue: 1,0:38:33.57,0:38:38.81,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}punishment of mistakes is sort of an interesting aspect
Dialogue: 0,0:38:33.57,0:38:38.81,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}对错误的惩罚是一个有趣的方面
Dialogue: 1,0:38:38.81,0:38:46.24,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like some puzzle games if you go back to the early uh like early 90s chip’s challenge style puzzly adventure games
Dialogue: 0,0:38:38.81,0:38:46.24,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你回到上世纪90年代早期，那种《Chip’s Challenge》风格的冒险解密游戏
Dialogue: 1,0:38:46.24,0:38:48.67,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}which had some real time and some turn-based elements
Dialogue: 0,0:38:46.24,0:38:48.67,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}里面有些实时的和回合制的元素
Dialogue: 1,0:38:48.67,0:38:50.33,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}many of those games were very punishing
Dialogue: 0,0:38:48.67,0:38:50.33,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这些游戏中很多的惩罚都非常重
Dialogue: 1,0:38:50.33,0:38:56.48,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like if you stepped the wrong way you'd have to completely restart the whole level you'd lose a life it was very frustrating
Dialogue: 0,0:38:50.33,0:38:56.48,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你走错了，你就得重新开始整个关卡或者丢失一条命，这让人很沮丧
Dialogue: 1,0:38:56.48,0:39:00.25,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um nowadays I think fewer games have that aesthetic
Dialogue: 0,0:38:56.48,0:39:00.25,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我觉得现在有这种审美的游戏越来越少了
Dialogue: 1,0:39:00.25,0:39:04.03,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and they're more uh you know they're more about solving the puzzles about their eureka moments
Dialogue: 0,0:39:00.25,0:39:04.03,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}现在的游戏更多是关注在解谜上，关注尤里卡时刻
Dialogue: 1,0:39:04.03,0:39:07.93,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and they allow undo and reset and you can often even undo your reset
Dialogue: 0,0:39:04.03,0:39:07.93,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而且它们允许撤销和重置，你甚至可以撤销你的重置
Dialogue: 1,0:39:07.93,0:39:10.75,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}which can be useful if you hit it by mistake um
Dialogue: 0,0:39:07.93,0:39:10.75,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你不小心按到重置按钮的话，这就很有用
Dialogue: 1,0:39:10.75,0:39:14.65,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}another big one is note taking and we'll get to this in the next section
Dialogue: 0,0:39:10.75,0:39:14.65,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}另一个重要的方面是做笔记，我们会在下一节中讨论这个问题
Dialogue: 1,0:39:14.65,0:39:22.91,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but essentially what I mean by note-taking is in the witness you just have to draw a line from the start to the end you can't sort of draw a partial line on the corner of the grid
Dialogue: 0,0:39:14.65,0:39:22.91,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但本质上说，在《见证者》中，你必须从头到尾画完整的一条先，你不能只画一部分的线
Dialogue: 1,0:39:22.91,0:39:32.64,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}whereas in alcazar the way you're making progress is by um sort of adding little bits of lines slowly until you've drawn in the whole path
Dialogue: 0,0:39:22.91,0:39:32.64,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而在《Alcazar》中，你是一点点加上小线段，知道你画出整条路径
Dialogue: 1,0:39:32.64,0:39:36.03,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and the experience of solving those two puzzles is very different
Dialogue: 0,0:39:32.64,0:39:36.03,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而解决这两个谜题的体验是非常不同的
Dialogue: 1,0:39:36.03,0:39:43.65,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}Note-taking can increase depth and this is you know an important enough uh lesson to be a number of its own
Dialogue: 0,0:39:36.03,0:39:43.65,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}「记笔记可以增加深度」，这一点还比较重要，值得单独列出来
Dialogue: 1,0:39:43.65,0:39:48.38,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}I want to show you an example in sudoku and then we will go back to the path drawing puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:39:43.65,0:39:48.38,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}我想给你们看一个数独的例子，然后我们再回来看前面画线谜题的例子
Dialogue: 1,0:39:48.38,0:39:56.45,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}a lot of players have had different ways of doing sudoku notation but they're sort of three that are most in in common use
Dialogue: 0,0:39:48.38,0:39:56.45,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}很多玩家都有不同的方法来做数独的记号，但这是最常用的三种
Dialogue: 1,0:39:56.45,0:40:00.41,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh and many sudoku solvers are using all three of these notations at once
Dialogue: 0,0:39:56.45,0:40:00.41,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}还有许多数独解题者同时使用这三种记法
Dialogue: 1,0:40:00.41,0:40:04.77,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}they're sort of candidate notation meaning this cell must contain one of these numbers
Dialogue: 0,0:40:00.41,0:40:04.77,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}一种是候选记号（Candidate notation），意思是格子中一定是这些数字之一
Dialogue: 1,0:40:04.77,0:40:07.71,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you know seven two means this cell is either a seven or a two
Dialogue: 0,0:40:04.77,0:40:07.71,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}写成“72”就意味着这个格子里要么是7要么是2
Dialogue: 1,0:40:07.71,0:40:12.77,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh Snyder notation is sort of the reverse it's this number goes in one of these cells
Dialogue: 0,0:40:07.71,0:40:12.77,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而Snyder记号是一种相反的记号，就是这个数字要放到这些格子中的一个位置
Dialogue: 1,0:40:12.77,0:40:16.86,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like here's a box the two in this box goes in one of these cells
Dialogue: 0,0:40:12.77,0:40:16.86,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}比如有这么个框，2就会放入这个框中的其中一格
Dialogue: 1,0:40:16.86,0:40:22.17,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and sometimes you sort of draw a two on the border between two boxes it's sometimes called a bivalue
Dialogue: 0,0:40:16.86,0:40:22.17,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}有时你会在两个框交界的地方写个2，这有时被叫做“bivalue”
Dialogue: 1,0:40:22.17,0:40:25.12,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}there's different ways that people do it and annotate it
Dialogue: 0,0:40:22.17,0:40:25.12,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}人们有不同的方法来做这样的记号和注释
Dialogue: 1,0:40:25.12,0:40:30.37,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and then there are colors which means these two cells are the same number but I don't know which one they are yet
Dialogue: 0,0:40:25.12,0:40:30.37,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然后还有涂色记号，意味着两个格子数字相同，但还不确定是什么数字
Dialogue: 1,0:40:30.37,0:40:36.96,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um and this is an example from cracking the cryptic where here Mark Goodlife is filling out this grid
Dialogue: 0,0:40:30.37,0:40:36.96,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这里这个例子来自Cracking the Cryptic频道，Mark Goodlife正在填这个格子
Dialogue: 2,0:40:36.96,0:40:43.55,Annote,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}（译者注：这是一个温度计数独，含温度计的格子从头部开始数字增大）
Dialogue: 1,0:40:36.96,0:40:43.55,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and hasn't put in a single number yet or he's just put in his first number which is a seven over here uh in this thermometer
Dialogue: 0,0:40:36.96,0:40:43.55,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}还没有填上一个数字，或者说他刚刚填了第一个数字，也就是这个温度计里的7
Dialogue: 1,0:40:43.55,0:40:46.69,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and uh it took him 30 minutes to get this far
Dialogue: 0,0:40:43.55,0:40:46.69,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}他走到当前这个状态花了30分钟
Dialogue: 1,0:40:46.69,0:40:50.53,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but after he put in that seven he was then able to finish the whole puzzle in less than a minute
Dialogue: 0,0:40:46.69,0:40:50.53,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但当他填入7后，他就能在一分钟内完成整个谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:40:50.53,0:40:53.21,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because as soon as you get one number the whole thing collapses um
Dialogue: 0,0:40:50.53,0:40:53.21,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为一旦你得到一个数字，整个谜题就会“崩塌”
Dialogue: 1,0:40:53.21,0:40:57.50,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but this type of puzzle would not be solvable without note taking
Dialogue: 0,0:40:53.21,0:40:57.50,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但这种类型的谜题如果不做笔记的话是无法解决的
Dialogue: 1,0:40:57.50,0:41:03.65,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like you can't solve it the way you would in normal sudoku where you're just putting in one number then the next then the next then the next then the next
Dialogue: 0,0:40:57.50,0:41:03.65,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你不能像普通的数独游戏那样，先填一个数字，然后再一个接一个填
Dialogue: 1,0:41:03.65,0:41:08.89,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you need to be able to take notes and sort of reduce the possibility space down from this large you know
Dialogue: 0,0:41:03.65,0:41:08.89,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你需要做笔记，把这么大的可能性空间给缩小
Dialogue: 1,0:41:08.89,0:41:12.09,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}so many things could be the answer down to only these things could be the answer
Dialogue: 0,0:41:08.89,0:41:12.09,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}从很多东西都可以是答案，到只有这些才是答案
Dialogue: 1,0:41:12.09,0:41:15.61,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and then from there you realize ah this number has to go there
Dialogue: 0,0:41:12.09,0:41:15.61,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}然后你就会意识到，这个数字一定要放在那里
Dialogue: 1,0:41:15.61,0:41:21.05,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um and so the eureka moments that are possible with note taking are much deeper than those without it
Dialogue: 0,0:41:15.61,0:41:21.05,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以，含有记笔记过程的尤里卡时刻，要比那些没有的要深刻得多
Dialogue: 1,0:41:21.05,0:41:25.60,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}let's go back to the witness this is an example from it's very early in the game
Dialogue: 0,0:41:21.05,0:41:25.60,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}让我们回到《见证者》来，这是游戏前期的一个例子
Dialogue: 1,0:41:25.60,0:41:30.78,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}in fact that you see this puzzle and there's multiple start locations multiple places where you could possibly end it
Dialogue: 0,0:41:25.60,0:41:30.78,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}事实上，你看到这个谜题之后会发现，它有多个起点和终点
Dialogue: 1,0:41:30.78,0:41:40.38,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}the goal is basically you have to draw a single line from one of those start locations to an end location that both passes through all these black hexagons
Dialogue: 0,0:41:30.78,0:41:40.38,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}目标是你必须从其中一个起点位置画一条线到终点，同时穿过所有这些黑色的六边形
Dialogue: 1,0:41:40.38,0:41:48.06,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}as well as um well it has to cut the light and dark cells uh so that they don't live in the same connected component
Dialogue: 0,0:41:40.38,0:41:48.06,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}同时还得把含有黑块和白块的格子分隔开来，使得它们在不同的连通分量当中
Dialogue: 1,0:41:48.06,0:41:59.13,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and there's a long uh you know definition of what that really is but it sort of is like keeping all the light cells on the left and dark cells on the right or vice versa it's similar to that
Dialogue: 0,0:41:48.06,0:41:59.13,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}基本上就是说让所有含黑块的格子在线一边，含有白块的格子在线的另一边
Dialogue: 1,0:41:59.13,0:42:02.97,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um and if you sort of take this puzzle into MS paint
Dialogue: 0,0:41:59.13,0:42:02.97,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而如果你把这个谜题截屏放到画图里面看
Dialogue: 1,0:42:02.97,0:42:09.44,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you could kind of draw in some little bits of deductive analysis of where the path must go
Dialogue: 0,0:42:02.97,0:42:09.44,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你就可以推理分析出一些小线段来代表路径必须经过的地方
Dialogue: 1,0:42:09.44,0:42:12.83,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and from here you can actually solve the puzzle pretty easily
Dialogue: 0,0:42:09.44,0:42:12.83,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而根据这个你可以很容易地解决这个谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:42:12.83,0:42:16.86,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh but that's sort of not really the way this puzzle is designed right
Dialogue: 0,0:42:12.83,0:42:16.86,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但这个谜题设计出来并不是这样的方式，对吗？
Dialogue: 1,0:42:16.86,0:42:21.60,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it's not a puzzle where you can enter partial bits of progress while playing it
Dialogue: 0,0:42:16.86,0:42:21.60,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这不是那种你玩的时候一小截一小截线段往里添加的谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:42:21.60,0:42:28.51,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it's a puzzle game where you sort of start at the beginning and then draw a line out and it goes through everything and exits
Dialogue: 0,0:42:21.60,0:42:28.51,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这是你得从起点开始画一条线、穿过所有东西直到终点的谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:42:28.51,0:42:36.64,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}this isn't necessarily a bad thing but it does limit the complexity of the types of puzzles that you could create in the witness
Dialogue: 0,0:42:28.51,0:42:36.64,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这不一定是件坏事，但它也的确限制了《见证者》中能创作的谜题的复杂性
Dialogue: 1,0:42:36.64,0:42:40.61,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like if you go back to this Alcazar puzzle on the right hand side here
Dialogue: 0,0:42:36.64,0:42:40.61,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}就比如我们回到之前那个《Alcazar》的谜题，在右手边这个
Dialogue: 1,0:42:40.61,0:42:45.09,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}you could never make this in the puzzle in the witness because it would just be too frustrating for players
Dialogue: 0,0:42:40.61,0:42:45.09,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你永远不可能在《见证者》中做这样一个谜题，因为这会让玩家非常懊恼
Dialogue: 1,0:42:45.09,0:42:53.28,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like they would literally need to print screen it and go into paint because you can't necessarily solve it start to end without making a mistake
Dialogue: 0,0:42:45.09,0:42:53.28,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}你真的可能得截个屏然后放到画图里来看，你不可能从头到尾不犯错画根线就把它解出来了
Dialogue: 1,0:42:53.28,0:42:58.91,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um it's just sort of too much for the player's working memory to be able to do that in their head right
Dialogue: 0,0:42:53.28,0:42:58.91,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这对玩家的短期记忆能力来说实在是太多了，不可能就在脑海里完成这个任务
Dialogue: 1,0:42:58.91,0:43:01.79,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it's too big of a grid for you to be able to head solve
Dialogue: 0,0:42:58.91,0:43:01.79,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这个网格太大了，不可能在脑海里解出来的
Dialogue: 1,0:43:01.79,0:43:05.82,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and so, the witness fundamentally limits itself to smaller grids
Dialogue: 0,0:43:01.79,0:43:05.82,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因此，《见证者》从根本上说限制了自己只能使用较小一点的网格
Dialogue: 1,0:43:05.82,0:43:09.28,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because it wants to you know have grids that people can head solve
Dialogue: 0,0:43:05.82,0:43:09.28,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为它希望它的网格能直接让人在脑海里解出来
Dialogue: 1,0:43:09.28,0:43:12.41,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}rather than grids that people are going to need to take a million notes for
Dialogue: 0,0:43:09.28,0:43:12.41,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而不是需要人们去做无数的笔记
Dialogue: 1,0:43:12.41,0:43:16.83,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but that sort of limits how deep and interesting those puzzles can be
Dialogue: 0,0:43:12.41,0:43:16.83,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但这同时也限制那些谜题的深度和趣味性
Dialogue: 1,0:43:16.83,0:43:20.29,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}now that said taking notes isn't necessarily a good fit for the theme of the witness
Dialogue: 0,0:43:16.83,0:43:20.29,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}虽然这么说，但做笔记本身不一定适合《见证者》的主题
Dialogue: 1,0:43:20.29,0:43:24.45,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}the witness is fundamentally a game about drawing a line from one place to the next
Dialogue: 0,0:43:20.29,0:43:24.45,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}《见证者》从根本上说就是从一点到另一点画线的游戏
Dialogue: 1,0:43:24.45,0:43:28.35,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and not a game about note-taking when you're solving logic puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:43:24.45,0:43:28.35,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而不是要求边解逻辑谜题边做笔记的游戏
Dialogue: 1,0:43:28.35,0:43:32.38,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um so I think the witnesses approach is correct for what the witness is trying to do
Dialogue: 0,0:43:28.35,0:43:32.38,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}所以我认为《见证者》的方法对于《见证者》本身所要尝试做的事情来说，是正确的
Dialogue: 1,0:43:32.38,0:43:37.63,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}um but I’m just saying it does create some limitation in what types of puzzles can be expressed
Dialogue: 0,0:43:32.38,0:43:37.63,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但我还是得说它对能够表达的谜题类型产生了一些限制
Dialogue: 1,0:43:37.63,0:43:42.05,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}or you know can be expressed in a way that's convenient for the solver to access
Dialogue: 0,0:43:37.63,0:43:42.05,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}或者说（它限制了）那种能够用让玩家可以方便解出来的方式表达的
Dialogue: 1,0:43:42.05,0:43:50.94,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}without copy pasting the puzzle into MS paint or taking notes on paper or trying to keep way too many things in their head at once
Dialogue: 0,0:43:42.05,0:43:50.94,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而不需要把谜题粘贴到画图中，或者在纸上做笔记，或者在脑海中记太多东西的谜题
Dialogue: 1,0:43:51.01,0:43:57.66,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}some puzzles are basically designed such that note taking is the solution to the puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:43:51.01,0:43:57.66,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而有些谜题基本上就是把记笔记作为谜题的解决步骤
Dialogue: 1,0:43:57.66,0:43:59.13,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}minesweeper is one of them
Dialogue: 0,0:43:57.66,0:43:59.13,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}扫雷就是其中之一
Dialogue: 1,0:43:59.13,0:44:03.23,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}if you try solving minesweeper without noting the mines it's really hard
Dialogue: 0,0:43:59.13,0:44:03.23,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}如果你试着不标记地雷的位置来解开扫雷，那真的很困难
Dialogue: 1,0:44:03.23,0:44:07.77,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but also even just noting where the numbers are that is the form of progress of the puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:44:03.23,0:44:07.77,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但即便只是去留意数字的位置，那也是解谜取得进展的一种形式
Dialogue: 1,0:44:07.77,0:44:11.36,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like note-taking is progress it feels like progress
Dialogue: 0,0:44:07.77,0:44:11.36,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}记笔记就是一种进展，它感觉上就像取得了进展一样
Dialogue: 1,0:44:11.36,0:44:15.58,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}uh for these types of zebra crossing or Einstein’s riddle type puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:44:11.36,0:44:15.58,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}对于这种《斑马难题》
Dialogue: 1,0:44:15.58,0:44:20.64,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}where they give you a bunch of uh sort of logical hints and then you have to fill in the grid
Dialogue: 0,0:44:15.58,0:44:20.64,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}里面给你一些逻辑线索，然后你得填上这个表格
Dialogue: 1,0:44:20.64,0:44:27.55,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}like you know who had the milk who had the water you know who was what color etc
Dialogue: 0,0:44:20.64,0:44:27.55,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}比如给你线索说，谁喜欢喝牛奶，谁喜欢喝水，谁的房子是什么颜色等等
Dialogue: 1,0:44:27.55,0:44:32.54,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}those types of puzzles that the note taking is the progress it's what you're doing when you're solving the puzzle
Dialogue: 0,0:44:27.55,0:44:32.54,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}对这种类型的谜题，记笔记就是取得进展，就是你在解谜时做的事情
Dialogue: 1,0:44:32.54,0:44:36.57,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and this is often true of many types of logic puzzles and paper logic puzzles
Dialogue: 0,0:44:32.54,0:44:36.57,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}很多类型的逻辑谜题和纸质逻辑谜题都是如此
Dialogue: 1,0:44:36.57,0:44:45.28,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and it is a tradition that isn't used as much in video game puzzles that sort of rely more on statefulness and interaction
Dialogue: 0,0:44:36.57,0:44:45.28,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}而这一传统在电子游戏谜题中并不常有，电子游戏谜题更依赖于状态和交互
Dialogue: 1,0:44:45.28,0:44:48.86,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}because that you know this is a natural fit to pen and paper
Dialogue: 0,0:44:45.28,0:44:48.86,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}因为你知道，（做笔记）很自然地使用于纸上游戏
Dialogue: 1,0:44:48.86,0:44:53.47,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}it's less of a natural fit when you're playing a game and moving a character around in three-dimensional space
Dialogue: 0,0:44:48.86,0:44:53.47,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}但当你在三维空间中移动一个角色时，它就不那么自然了
Dialogue: 1,0:44:53.47,0:44:57.25,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}but they do a good job of making note-taking feel like progress
Dialogue: 0,0:44:53.47,0:44:57.25,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}不过（纸上游戏）在让人通过记笔记感到取得进展这方面做得很好
Dialogue: 1,0:44:57.25,0:45:01.98,Eng,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}and that's how they're able to access their depth in a way that isn't too annoying
Dialogue: 0,0:44:57.25,0:45:01.98,Chi,,0,0,0,,{\fad(120,120)}这就是他们如何能够以一种不太令人讨厌的方式拓展它们游戏的深度